<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1127,889,1329]" pageId="4" pageNumber="539">
The species is usually strongly brachypterous to almost micropterous (
<figureCitation box="[893,962,889,913]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[151,190,1230,1249]" captionTargetBox="[183,1094,218,1202]" captionTargetId="figure-11@2.[183,1095,217,1202]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–4. Wing polymorphic Sphaeroceridae. 1 – Crumomyia pedestris (Meigen, 1830), brachypterous male, body length 3.4 mm (Czech Republic: Úvalenské louky res. nr. Krnov); 2 – Pteremis fenestralis (Fallén, 1820), brachypterous male, body length 1.5 mm (Czech Republic: Jizerské hory Mts.– Jizerka); 3–4 – Pullimosina (Pullimosina) meijerei (Duda, 1918): 3 – macropterous female, body length 1.6 mm (Slovakia: Muránska planina Mts. – Šarkanica res.); 4 – male with ambiguous wings, body length 1.45 mm (Slovakia: Muránska planina Mts. – Bobačka cave env.). Photos by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332513/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="539">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[973,1029,889,913]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[113,152,1499,1518]" captionTargetBox="[134,1068,219,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[133,1068,219,1472]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 5–11. Crumomyia pedestris (Meigen, 1830), wings. 5 – macropterous female; 6 – submacropterous female (both Slovakia: Tatranská Kotlina – Šarpanec); 7 – large brachypterous female; 8 – medium brachypterous female; 9 – strongly brachypterous female; 10 – almost micropterous male (all Czech Republic: Úvalenské louky res. nr. Krnov); 11 – macropterous male with additional dm-cu cross-vein (Slovakia: Tatranská Kotlina – Šarpanec). Scale: 0.5 mm. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332515" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332515/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="539">7–10</figureCitation>
).Already 
<bibRefCitation author="GUIBE J." box="[151,288,921,945]" pageId="4" pageNumber="539" pagination="1 - 112" refId="ref9262" refString="GUIBE J. 1939: Contribution a l'etude d'une espece: Apterina pedestris Meigen (Diptere). Bulletin Biologique de la France et de la Belgique, Supplement 29: 1 - 112." type="journal article" year="1939">GUIBÉ (1939)</bibRefCitation>
obtained macropterous specimens during his breeding experiments but suggested that they are less viable. On the basis of his results 
<bibRefCitation author="RICHARDS O. W." box="[658,829,953,977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="539" pagination="829 - 851" refId="ref9550" refString="RICHARDS O. W. 1951: Brachypterous Sphaeroceridae. British Museum (Natural History) Ruwenzori Expedition, 1934 - 1935, 2 (8): 829 - 851." type="journal article" year="1951">RICHARDS (1951)</bibRefCitation>
stated that only the dominant micropterous homozygotes and heterozygotes occur in the wild. However, since 1975 the macropterous specimens were also found in the field several times (
<bibRefCitation author="ROHACEK J." box="[768,935,1017,1041]" pageId="4" pageNumber="539" pagination="196 - 207" refId="ref9644" refString="ROHACEK J. 1975 b: Die Flugelpolymorphie bei den europaischen Sphaeroceridenarten und Taxonomie der Limosina heteroneura-Gruppe (Diptera). Acta Entomologica Bohemoslovaca 72: 196 - 207." type="journal article" year="1975">
<subScript attach="right" box="[768,863,1017,1041]" fontSize="7" pageId="4" pageNumber="539">ROHÁČEK</subScript>
1975b
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="ROHACEK J." box="[943,998,1017,1041]" pageId="4" pageNumber="539" pagination="1 - 27" refId="ref9900" refString="ROHACEK J. 1991: Sphaeroceridae (Diptera) of Czechoslovakia. Part 2. Crumomyia Macquart. Casopis Slezskeho Zemskeho Muzea, Opava (A) 40: 1 - 27." type="journal article" year="1991">1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP L." box="[1007,1115,1017,1041]" pageId="4" pageNumber="539" pagination="75 - 86" refId="ref9483" refString="PAPP L. 1976: Some terricolous Sphaerocerids and Drosophilids from Hungary (Diptera: Sphaeroceridae and Drosophilidae). Folia Entomologica Hungarica, S. N. 29 (1): 75 - 86." type="journal article" year="1976">PAPP 1976</bibRefCitation>
). Originally (
<bibRefCitation author="ROHACEK J." box="[272,440,1049,1073]" pageId="4" pageNumber="539" pagination="196 - 207" refId="ref9644" refString="ROHACEK J. 1975 b: Die Flugelpolymorphie bei den europaischen Sphaeroceridenarten und Taxonomie der Limosina heteroneura-Gruppe (Diptera). Acta Entomologica Bohemoslovaca 72: 196 - 207." type="journal article" year="1975">
<subScript attach="right" box="[272,367,1049,1073]" fontSize="7" pageId="4" pageNumber="539">ROHÁČEK</subScript>
1975b
</bibRefCitation>
) I considered the macropterous and submacropterous forms (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[113,152,1499,1518]" captionTargetBox="[134,1068,219,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[133,1068,219,1472]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 5–11. Crumomyia pedestris (Meigen, 1830), wings. 5 – macropterous female; 6 – submacropterous female (both Slovakia: Tatranská Kotlina – Šarpanec); 7 – large brachypterous female; 8 – medium brachypterous female; 9 – strongly brachypterous female; 10 – almost micropterous male (all Czech Republic: Úvalenské louky res. nr. Krnov); 11 – macropterous male with additional dm-cu cross-vein (Slovakia: Tatranská Kotlina – Šarpanec). Scale: 0.5 mm. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332515" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332515/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="539">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
) to be atavistic specimens very rarely occurring among the usual micropterous specimens in natural populations. This opinion proved to be incorrect in the light of recent findings. The macropterous forms (
<figureCitation box="[371,430,1145,1169]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[113,152,1499,1518]" captionTargetBox="[134,1068,219,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[133,1068,219,1472]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 5–11. Crumomyia pedestris (Meigen, 1830), wings. 5 – macropterous female; 6 – submacropterous female (both Slovakia: Tatranská Kotlina – Šarpanec); 7 – large brachypterous female; 8 – medium brachypterous female; 9 – strongly brachypterous female; 10 – almost micropterous male (all Czech Republic: Úvalenské louky res. nr. Krnov); 11 – macropterous male with additional dm-cu cross-vein (Slovakia: Tatranská Kotlina – Šarpanec). Scale: 0.5 mm. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332515" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332515/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="539">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) seem to occur in only some populations, particularly in those living in drier habitats, e.g. in runs of small mammals. However, the preferred habitats of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1830" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Crumomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="539" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pedestris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="539">Crumomyia pedestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very damp meadows and boggy alder forests where its larvae develop in dead snails. In my opinion the wing polymorphism and, subsequently, the now prevailing strong brachyptery evolved in consequence of the adaptation of this species to the extreme humidity of its preferred habitat niche where long wings are strongly disadvantageous.
</paragraph>
